info.description: The following is a reference of the StackGo API which describes the request and response patterns for being able to use StackGo as the nexus of all your OAuth based API credentials. Please feel free to contact the [team](team@stackgo.io) in case of any queries or clarifications
info.title: StackGo API overview

get.description: Use this endpoint to generate an `Authorisation Link` for a set of Atlassian credentials registered on StackGo collectively referenced by the `appSlug` and a specific user referenced via `userForeignIdentifier`

parameters.name: userForeignIdentifier
parameters.description: Unique reference to a "user" in your application context. Can be a email address, UUID, Tenancy ID or similar
If true, it automatically redirects the caller to the SaaS platform. In this case Atlassian
parameters.name: redirect

200.description: The response for contains a customised intallation link for the `userForeignIdentifier`. This response can be used in the `connected accounts` or the `integrations` page of your app inviting the users to authorise your application to access their tools.

get.description: Use this endpoint to generate an `Authorisation Link` for a set of Procore credentials registered on StackGo collectively referenced by the `appSlug` and a specific user referenced via `userForeignIdentifier`

parameters.name: userForeignIdentifier
parameters.description: Unique reference to a "user" in your application context. Can be a email address, UUID, Tenancy ID or similar
If true, it automatically redirects the caller to the SaaS platform. In this case Atlassian
parameters.name: redirect

200.description: The response for contains a customised intallation link for the `userForeignIdentifier`. This response can be used in the `connected accounts` or the `integrations` page of your app inviting the users to authorise your application to access their tools.

get.description: Use this endpoint to generate an `Authorisation Link` for a set of Service Now credentials registered on StackGo collectively referenced by the `appSlug` and a specific user referenced via `userForeignIdentifier`

parameters.name: userForeignIdentifier
parameters.description: Unique reference to a "user" in your application context. Can be a email address, UUID, Tenancy ID or similar
If true, it automatically redirects the caller to the SaaS platform. In this case Atlassian
parameters.name: redirect

200.description: The response for contains a customised intallation link for the `userForeignIdentifier`. This response can be used in the `connected accounts` or the `integrations` page of your app inviting the users to authorise your application to access their tools.

post.description: Use this endpoint for proxying calls to the Atlassian platform using credentials referenced by the `appSlug` and against a end-user referenced by `userForeignIdentifier`. Any endpoints listed on  `https://developer.atlassian.com` can be used in this way.

parameters.name: Authorization
parameters.description: See [here](https://docs.stackgo.io/docs/stackgo-docs/All-OpenApi3Json.json/paths/~1oauth~1token/post) on how to generate the StackGo tokens

url.description: The actual `url` endpoint you would like to access

body.description: Optional. Provide the body of the request for 'POST` or `PUT` calls

requestBody.description: The request body is basically a structure to describe a HTTP call you would like to execute against the Atlassian suite of tools.

200.description: StackGo will check for tokens matching `userForeignIdentifier`, `appSlug` and then place a request to Atlassian. Any results or errors are transparently passed to the the API consumer.

Know your spaces 

Everything your team is working on - meeting notes and agendas, project plans and timelines, technical documentation and more - is located in a space; it's home base for your team.

A small team should plan to have a space for the team, and a space for each big project. If you'll be working in Confluence with several other teams and departments, we recommend a space for each team as well as a space for each major cross-team project. The key is to think of a space as the container that holds all the important stuff - like pages, files, and blog posts - a team, group, or project needs to work.

Know your pages

If you're working on something related to your team - project plans, product requirements, blog posts, internal communications, you name it - create and store it in a Confluence page. Confluence pages offer a lot of flexibility in creating and storing information, and there are a number of useful page templates included to get you started, like the meeting notes template. Your spaces should be filled with pages that document your business processes, outline your plans, contain your files, and report on your progress. The more you learn to do in Confluence (adding tables and graphs, or embedding video and links are great places to start), the more engaging and helpful your pages will become.

Learn more by reading Confluence 101: organize your work in spaces

 

Quick navigation

When you create new pages in this space, they'll appear here automatically.

Useful links

LinkDescription
Confluence 101: organize your work in spaces

Chances are, the information you need to do your job lives in multiple places. Word docs, Evernote files, email, PDFs, even Post-it notes. It's scattered among different systems. And to make matters worse, the stuff your teammates need is equally siloed. If information had feelings, it would be lonely.

But with Confluence, you can bring all that information into one place.

Confluence 101: discuss work with your teamGetting a project outlined and adding the right content are just the first steps. Now it's time for your team to weigh in. Confluence makes it easy to discuss your work - with your team, your boss, or your entire company - in the same place where you organized and created it.
Confluence 101: create content with pagesThink of pages as a New Age "document." If Word docs were rotary phones, Confluence pages would be smart phones. A smart phone still makes calls (like their rotary counterparts), but it can do so much more than that

Know your spaces 

Everything your team is working on - meeting notes and agendas, project plans and timelines, technical documentation and more - is located in a space; it's home base for your team.

A small team should plan to have a space for the team, and a space for each big project. If you'll be working in Confluence with several other teams and departments, we recommend a space for each team as well as a space for each major cross-team project. The key is to think of a space as the container that holds all the important stuff - like pages, files, and blog posts - a team, group, or project needs to work.

Know your pages

If you're working on something related to your team - project plans, product requirements, blog posts, internal communications, you name it - create and store it in a Confluence page. Confluence pages offer a lot of flexibility in creating and storing information, and there are a number of useful page templates included to get you started, like the meeting notes template. Your spaces should be filled with pages that document your business processes, outline your plans, contain your files, and report on your progress. The more you learn to do in Confluence (adding tables and graphs, or embedding video and links are great places to start), the more engaging and helpful your pages will become.

Learn more by reading Confluence 101: organize your work in spaces

 

Quick navigation

When you create new pages in this space, they'll appear here automatically.

Useful links

LinkDescription
Confluence 101: organize your work in spaces

Chances are, the information you need to do your job lives in multiple places. Word docs, Evernote files, email, PDFs, even Post-it notes. It's scattered among different systems. And to make matters worse, the stuff your teammates need is equally siloed. If information had feelings, it would be lonely.

But with Confluence, you can bring all that information into one place.

Confluence 101: discuss work with your teamGetting a project outlined and adding the right content are just the first steps. Now it's time for your team to weigh in. Confluence makes it easy to discuss your work - with your team, your boss, or your entire company - in the same place where you organized and created it.
Confluence 101: create content with pagesThink of pages as a New Age "document." If Word docs were rotary phones, Confluence pages would be smart phones. A smart phone still makes calls (like their rotary counterparts), but it can do so much more than that
